## File Scope
Primary file: `src/debug-dashboard/index.ts`

## Problem
The debug dashboard inserts log messages, JSON data, error messages, stacks, config, and system info through `innerHTML`. These values can originate from Pushbullet payloads, API errors, WebSocket close reasons, or exception messages.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/debug-dashboard/index.ts
logsContainer.innerHTML = [...filteredLogs].reverse().map(log => {
  const dataStr = log.data ? JSON.stringify(log.data, null, 2) : '';
  const errorStr = log.error ? `${log.error.name}: ${log.error.message}` : '';

  return `
    <div class="log-entry ${log.level}">
      <div class="log-message">${log.message}</div>
      ${dataStr ? `<div class="log-data">${dataStr}</div>` : ''}
      ${errorStr ? `<div class="log-data error">${errorStr}</div>` : ''}
    </div>
  `;
}).join('');
```

## Mitigation
Use DOM construction and `textContent` for dynamic values.

```ts
const entry = document.createElement('div');
entry.className = `log-entry ${safeLogLevel(log.level)}`;

const message = document.createElement('div');
message.className = 'log-message';
message.textContent = log.message;
entry.appendChild(message);

if (log.data) {
  const pre = document.createElement('pre');
  pre.className = 'log-data';
  pre.textContent = JSON.stringify(log.data, null, 2);
  entry.appendChild(pre);
}

logsContainer.replaceChildren(entry);
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Log message/data/error rendering does not use string templates assigned to `innerHTML`.
- Critical error rendering does not interpolate error name, message, category, timestamp, or stack into HTML strings.
- Config/system JSON is rendered through `textContent` on `pre` nodes.
- Tests prove hostile HTML appears as text and does not create DOM elements.

## File Scope
Primary files:
- `src/lib/logging/index.ts`
- `src/background/index.ts`
- `src/background/utils.ts`
- `src/app/api/client.ts`
- `src/popup/index.ts`

## Problem
Debug logging captures complete decrypted pushes, SMS/file push objects, raw devices, and outbound push data. The sanitizer only redacts keys containing `token`, `key`, or `password`.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/background/index.ts
debugLogger.general("DEBUG", "FULL DECRYPTED PUSH DATA", {
  completeData: decryptedPush,
});
```

```ts
// src/background/utils.ts
debugLogger.notifications("DEBUG", "Complete sms_changed push object received", { push });
debugLogger.notifications("DEBUG", "Complete file push object received", { push });
```

```ts
// src/app/api/client.ts
debugLogger.general('INFO', `[DEVICE_DEBUG] Device #${index + 1}`, {
  pushToken: device.push_token ? `${device.push_token.substring(0, 8)}...` : '(no push token)',
  rawDevice: device,
});
```

## Mitigation
Replace full-object logs with summaries:

```ts
function summarizePush(push: Push): Record<string, unknown> {
  return {
    iden: push.iden,
    type: push.type,
    encrypted: !!push.encrypted,
    hasTitle: typeof push.title === 'string' && push.title.length > 0,
    hasBody: typeof push.body === 'string' && push.body.length > 0,
    hasUrl: typeof push.url === 'string' && push.url.length > 0,
    created: push.created,
    modified: push.modified,
  };
}
```

Expand redaction:

```ts
const SENSITIVE_KEYS = /token|key|password|secret|body|title|url|file_url|image_url|email|phone|address/i;

if (SENSITIVE_KEYS.test(key)) {
  sanitized[key] = '[redacted]';
} else {
  sanitized[key] = sanitize(value);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- `rg "FULL DECRYPTED|Complete sms_changed|Complete file push|rawDevice|pushData" src` has no sensitive full-payload logging sites.
- Exported logs redact `body`, `title`, `url`, `file_url`, `image_url`, `email`, phone-like fields, API keys, tokens, and passwords.
- Tests cover nested object redaction and arrays.

## Purpose
This phase handles the highest security and privacy findings. The extension processes decrypted messages, SMS text, links, file URLs, device records, and credentials. Debug paths currently persist and render too much of that data.

## Audit Evidence
```ts
// src/background/index.ts
debugLogger.general("DEBUG", "FULL DECRYPTED PUSH DATA", {
  completeData: decryptedPush,
});
```

```ts
// src/debug-dashboard/index.ts
logsContainer.innerHTML = [...filteredLogs].reverse().map(log => {
  const dataStr = log.data ? JSON.stringify(log.data, null, 2) : '';
  return `<div class="log-message">${log.message}</div>${dataStr}`;
}).join('');
```

These paths combine into a concrete privacy/render issue: private user content can be persisted in logs and inserted into extension page markup.

## Design Direction
Use allowlist logging and DOM-safe rendering.

```ts
function summarizePushForLog(push: Push): Record<string, unknown> {
  return {
    iden: push.iden,
    type: push.type,
    encrypted: !!push.encrypted,
    hasBody: typeof push.body === 'string' && push.body.length > 0,
    hasUrl: typeof push.url === 'string' && push.url.length > 0,
  };
}
```

## Success Criteria
- Full decrypted pushes are never logged.
- SMS bodies, note bodies, URLs, file URLs, raw device data, API keys, tokens, and passwords are redacted or omitted.
- Debug dashboard cannot execute markup supplied through logs or errors.
- Tests include hostile strings like `<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>` and verify text rendering.

## File Scope
Primary file: `src/app/reconnect/index.ts`

Call sites to update:
- `src/background/utils.ts`
- `src/background/index.ts`

## Problem
`ensureConfigLoaded()` returns successfully without doing anything when called without setters/getters. Several wake-related paths call it without arguments and then read `getApiKey()`, believing storage hydration happened.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/app/reconnect/index.ts
export async function ensureConfigLoaded(stateSetters?, stateGetters?): Promise<void> {
  if (!stateSetters || !stateGetters) {
    // No state management provided, just return
    return;
  }

  const apiKey = await storageRepository.getApiKey();
  stateSetters.setApiKey(apiKey);
}
```

Known bad pattern:

```ts
// src/background/utils.ts
await ensureConfigLoaded();
const apiKey = getApiKey();
```

## Mitigation
Remove the no-arg API or make it real in a background-owned wrapper.

Preferred explicit adapter call:

```ts
await ensureConfigLoaded(
  { setApiKey, setDeviceIden, setAutoOpenLinks, setDeviceNickname, setNotificationTimeout },
  { getApiKey, getDeviceIden, getAutoOpenLinks, getDeviceNickname, getNotificationTimeout },
);
```

Alternative wrapper:

```ts
// src/background/config.ts
export async function hydrateBackgroundConfig(): Promise<void> {
  await ensureConfigLoaded(backgroundSetters, backgroundGetters);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- `rg "ensureConfigLoaded\(\)" src` finds no silent no-op call sites, or each no-arg call invokes a real background hydrator.
- `SEND_PUSH` after service-worker wake can read the API key from storage.
- Health-check recovery reads storage before deciding recovery is impossible.

## Purpose
Fix the reliability root cause: after service-worker suspension or OS hibernate, the extension can wake with stale in-memory objects and a persisted `READY` state that no longer matches the actual WebSocket.

## Audit Evidence
Persisted `READY` is restored as if it were live operational truth:

```ts
// src/background/state-machine.ts
} else if (restoredState) {
  instance.currentState = restoredState;
  debugLogger.general("INFO", "[StateMachine] Hydrated state from storage", {
    restoredState: instance.currentState,
  });
}
```

Health check then detects a missing/disconnected socket but refuses to reconnect from `READY`:

```ts
// src/background/utils.ts
if (!websocketClient || !websocketClient.isConnected()) {
  const currentState = stateMachine.getCurrentState();

  if (currentState === ServiceWorkerState.IDLE) {
    stateMachine.transition("ATTEMPT_RECONNECT", { hasApiKey: true });
  } else if (currentState === ServiceWorkerState.DEGRADED || currentState === ServiceWorkerState.RECONNECTING) {
    connectFn();
  } else {
    debugLogger.websocket("DEBUG", "[HealthCheck] Skipping reconnect - unexpected state", { currentState });
  }
}
```

## Design Direction
Create one wake reconciliation path and call it from alarms, popup wake, manual reconnect, startup, and health check.

```ts
export async function reconcileWake(reason: string): Promise<void> {
  await hydrateBackgroundConfig();
  await stateMachineReady;
  ensureRecoveryAlarmsExist();

  const hasApiKey = !!getApiKey();
  const socketHealthy = !!websocketClient?.isConnected?.() && websocketClient.isConnectionHealthy();

  if (hasApiKey && !socketHealthy) {
    await stateMachine.transition('ATTEMPT_RECONNECT', {
      hasApiKey,
      socketHealthy,
      reason,
    });
  }
}
```

## Success Criteria
- `READY + null socket` reconnects.
- `READY + closed socket` reconnects.
- Reconnect decisions hydrate storage before reading `getApiKey()`.
- Permanent WebSocket close events use `WS_PERMANENT_ERROR`.
- Tests encode the hibernate-style stale `READY` state.

## Problem
When the host system hibernates and later resumes, the extension can wake with `lastKnownState = READY` but without a live WebSocket. The extension then displays or behaves as connected while real-time delivery is dead.

## Steps to Reproduce
1. Authenticate the extension and let it reach `READY`.
2. Hibernate or sleep the system long enough for the MV3 background service worker and socket to be gone.
3. Resume the system without restarting the browser.
4. Let an alarm fire or trigger manual wake.
5. Observe that the extension can remain on a stale `READY` path and fail to reconnect.

## Evidence
`READY` is restored as-is:

```ts
// src/background/state-machine.ts
} else if (restoredState) {
  instance.currentState = restoredState;
}
```

`READY` does not accept `ATTEMPT_RECONNECT`:

```ts
// src/background/state-machine.ts
case ServiceWorkerState.READY:
  if (event === 'WS_DISCONNECTED') return ServiceWorkerState.DEGRADED;
  if (event === 'WS_PERMANENT_ERROR') return ServiceWorkerState.ERROR;
  break;
```

Health check skips `READY + no socket`:

```ts
// src/background/utils.ts
if (!websocketClient || !websocketClient.isConnected()) {
  if (apiKey) {
    const currentState = stateMachine.getCurrentState();
    if (currentState === ServiceWorkerState.IDLE) {
      stateMachine.transition('ATTEMPT_RECONNECT', { hasApiKey: true });
    } else if (currentState === ServiceWorkerState.DEGRADED || currentState === ServiceWorkerState.RECONNECTING) {
      connectFn();
    } else {
      // READY lands here and no recovery happens.
    }
  }
}
```

## Mitigation
Treat persisted `READY` as UI history, not proof of a live socket. On wake, evaluate real credentials and socket health.

```ts
case ServiceWorkerState.READY:
  if (event === 'ATTEMPT_RECONNECT' && data?.hasApiKey && data?.socketHealthy === false) {
    return ServiceWorkerState.RECONNECTING;
  }
  if (event === 'WS_DISCONNECTED') return ServiceWorkerState.DEGRADED;
  if (event === 'WS_PERMANENT_ERROR') return ServiceWorkerState.ERROR;
  break;
```

The higher-value fix is a central reconciler:

```ts
await hydrateBackgroundConfig();
const socketHealthy = websocketClient?.isConnected?.() && websocketClient.isConnectionHealthy();
if (getApiKey() && !socketHealthy) {
  await stateMachine.transition('ATTEMPT_RECONNECT', { hasApiKey: true, socketHealthy: false });
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Hibernate/resume with saved credentials reconnects without opening the popup.
- `READY + missing socket` triggers reconnect.
- `READY + unhealthy socket` triggers reconnect.
- `longSleepRecovery`, `websocketHealthCheck`, popup wake, and manual `attemptReconnect` call the same reconciliation function.
- Tests cover persisted `READY`, no live socket, and API key present in storage.

## File Scope
Primary test files:
- `tests/lib/logging.test.ts`
- `tests/debug-dashboard/debug-dashboard.test.ts`
- `tests/background/utils.test.ts`
- `tests/lib/message-validation.test.ts`

## Problem
Security fixes need regression tests. Without tests, full-payload logging and unsafe dashboard rendering can return during future debugging.

## Evidence to Encode
```ts
const hostile = '<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>';
debugLogger.general('INFO', hostile, {
  body: 'private SMS body',
  url: 'https://example.com/private?token=abc',
});
```

Expected dashboard behavior:

```ts
expect(container.querySelector('img')).toBeNull();
expect(container.textContent).toContain('<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>');
```

Expected redaction behavior:

```ts
expect(exported).not.toContain('private SMS body');
expect(exported).not.toContain('https://example.com/private');
expect(exported).toContain('[redacted]');
```

URL validation cases:

```ts
expect(isTrustedImageUrl('http://a.pushbulletusercontent.com/x.png')).toBe(false);
expect(isTrustedImageUrl('https://a.pushbulletusercontent.com/x.png')).toBe(true);
expect(isTrustedImageUrl('javascript:alert(1)')).toBe(false);
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Logging tests cover nested objects and arrays.
- Dashboard tests prove hostile HTML is text, not DOM.
- Image URL tests require `https:`.
- Message contract tests prove every options action has a background handler or is not sent.

## File Scope
Primary test files:
- `tests/background/state-machine.test.ts`
- `tests/background/utils.test.ts`
- `tests/background/startup.test.ts`
- optional `tests/background/lifecycle.test.ts`

## Problem
The hibernate bug is a lifecycle state mismatch. Existing tests do not fully pin the stale `READY` scenario or storage hydration gap.

## Evidence to Encode
```ts
chrome.storage.local.get.mockResolvedValue({
  lastKnownState: ServiceWorkerState.READY,
  apiKey: 'test-api-key',
});
```

```ts
const websocketClient = null;
const currentState = ServiceWorkerState.READY;
```

Old broken behavior:

```ts
performWebSocketHealthCheck(null, connectWebSocket);
expect(connectWebSocket).not.toHaveBeenCalled(); // should become the opposite
```

## Mitigation Test Shape
```ts
it('reconnects when hydrated READY has no live websocket and storage has api key', async () => {
  mockGetApiKeyFromStorage('test-api-key');
  mockState(ServiceWorkerState.READY);

  await reconcileWake('test-hibernate-resume');

  expect(connectWebSocket).toHaveBeenCalled();
});
```

Permanent close mapping:

```ts
socket.onclose?.({ code: 1008, reason: 'auth', wasClean: true } as CloseEvent);
expect(stateMachine.transition).toHaveBeenCalledWith('WS_PERMANENT_ERROR');
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Test fails against old stale-READY behavior and passes after fix.
- Test covers memory API key empty but storage API key present.
- Test covers manual `attemptReconnect` after wake.
- Test covers permanent close event mapping.

## File Scope
Primary files:
- `src/background/index.ts`
- `src/background/startup.ts`
- `src/background/utils.ts`

## Problem
Lifecycle modules import each other in circles, and startup performs redundant initialization. That makes hibernate wake behavior harder to centralize.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/background/startup.ts
import { ensureDebugConfigLoadedOnce } from './index';
```

```ts
// src/background/index.ts
import { orchestrateInitialization } from "./startup";
```

```ts
// src/background/utils.ts
import { stateMachine } from "./index";
```

```ts
// src/background/index.ts
// onInitialize callback drives initialization, but this still runs too:
void orchestrateInitialization(trigger, connectWebSocket);
```

## Mitigation
Extract a lifecycle coordinator with explicit dependencies.

```ts
export interface LifecycleDeps {
  stateMachine: ServiceWorkerStateMachine;
  connectWebSocket: () => void;
  hydrateConfig: () => Promise<void>;
}

export function createLifecycleCoordinator(deps: LifecycleDeps) {
  return {
    bootstrap: (trigger: string) => bootstrapWithDeps(trigger, deps),
    reconcileWake: (reason: string) => reconcileWakeWithDeps(reason, deps),
  };
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- `startup.ts` does not import from `index.ts`.
- `utils.ts` does not import `stateMachine` from `index.ts`.
- Bootstrap has a single initialization owner.
- Tests prove startup does not duplicate orchestration.

## File Scope
Primary files:
- `src/options/index.ts`
- `src/background/index.ts`
- `src/types/domain.ts`
- `src/lib/security/message-validation.ts`

## Problem
Options sends action types that are declared and privileged, but background does not handle them.

## Evidence
```ts
chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  action: MessageAction.AUTO_OPEN_LINKS_CHANGED,
  autoOpenLinks: enabled
});

chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  action: MessageAction.ENCRYPTION_PASSWORD_CHANGED,
  hasPassword: password.length > 0
});

chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  action: MessageAction.DEBUG_MODE_CHANGED,
  enabled: enabled
});
```

Background handles `SETTINGS_CHANGED`, `UPDATE_DEBUG_CONFIG`, and others, but not these action names.

## Mitigation
Prefer one settings message shape:

```ts
chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  action: MessageAction.SETTINGS_CHANGED,
  settings: { autoOpenLinks: enabled },
});
```

Use existing debug config action:

```ts
chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  action: MessageAction.UPDATE_DEBUG_CONFIG,
  config: { enabled },
});
```

If encryption password changes require background behavior, add a handler. If not, remove the message and enum value.

## Acceptance Criteria
- No options message falls through background unhandled.
- `MessageAction` contains only active contracts.
- Privileged validation matches real privileged handlers.
- Tests cover settings messages.

## Purpose
Reduce architecture drift. Background is intended to be the API/session source of truth, but popup/options still own some API and storage behavior directly. Lifecycle modules also import each other in circles.

## Audit Evidence
Message drift:

```ts
// src/options/index.ts
chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  action: MessageAction.AUTO_OPEN_LINKS_CHANGED,
  autoOpenLinks: enabled,
});
```

Background has no matching handler for that action.

Popup API bypass:

```ts
// src/popup/index.ts
const uploadApiKey = await storageRepository.getApiKey();
const uploadRequestResponse = await fetch(
  "https://api.pushbullet.com/v2/upload-request",
  { headers: { "Access-Token": uploadApiKey } },
);
```

Circular lifecycle import:

```ts
// src/background/startup.ts
import { ensureDebugConfigLoadedOnce } from './index';
```

## Success Criteria
- Every message action sent by options/popup has a background handler or is removed.
- API calls requiring the Pushbullet token are owned by background, except documented exceptions.
- Startup/wake/reconnect lifecycle modules no longer import each other cyclically.
- Popup session data loads cache-first and refreshes in the background.

## File Scope
Primary files:
- `src/background/utils.ts`
- `src/app/session/pipeline.ts`
- `src/app/session/index.ts`
- `src/infrastructure/storage/storage.repository.ts`

## Problem
`lastModifiedCutoff` is advanced before downstream side effects are complete. The cursor means "fetched" rather than "processed."

## Evidence
```ts
// src/background/utils.ts
const incrementalPushes = await fetchIncrementalPushes(apiKey, cutoff, 100);

if (maxModified > cutoff) {
  sessionCache.lastModifiedCutoff = maxModified;
  await setLastModifiedCutoffSafe(maxModified);
}

// notification and auto-open work happens after this point
```

```ts
// src/app/session/pipeline.ts
const pushes = await fetchIncrementalPushes(apiKey, storedCutoff, 100);
const maxModified = await computeMaxModified(pushes);
if (maxModified > storedCutoff!) {
  await setLastModifiedCutoffSafe(maxModified);
}
return { pushes, isSeedRun: false as const };
```

## Mitigation
Use a pending queue or per-push processed marker.

```ts
await storageRepository.savePendingPushes(incrementalPushes.map(p => ({
  iden: p.iden,
  modified: p.modified,
  status: 'pending',
})));

await processPendingPushes();
await setLastModifiedCutoffSafe(maxProcessedModified);
```

Or:

```ts
for (const push of incrementalPushes) {
  if (await storageRepository.wasPushProcessed(push.iden)) continue;
  await showPushNotification(push, notificationDataStore);
  await maybeAutoOpenLinkWithDismiss(push);
  await storageRepository.markPushProcessed(push.iden, push.modified);
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Test throws after fetch and before notification; next run still processes the push.
- Test throws after one push is processed; next run processes remaining pushes only.
- `lastModifiedCutoff` means processed-through.

## Purpose
Fix correctness issues in data processing. The extension currently updates durable cursors before side effects finish. That is risky in MV3 because the service worker can stop between awaits.

## Audit Evidence
```ts
const incrementalPushes = await fetchIncrementalPushes(apiKey, cutoff, 100);
await setLastModifiedCutoffSafe(maxModified);
// notifications and auto-open happen after this point
```

If the worker dies after the cutoff write but before notification or auto-open, the next run skips those pushes.

## Design Direction
Separate observation from completed processing.

```ts
type PushProcessingRecord = {
  iden: string;
  modified: number;
  status: 'pending' | 'processed' | 'failed';
};
```

A simpler idempotent marker design is acceptable:

```ts
if (!(await wasPushProcessed(push.iden))) {
  await showPushNotification(push, store);
  await markPushProcessed(push.iden, push.modified);
}
```

## Success Criteria
- Worker death after fetch but before notification does not skip pushes permanently.
- Large catch-up fetches do not silently drop pages.
- Notification timeout setting applies to received notifications or is renamed/removed.
- Logger persistence cannot overwrite logs produced before rehydrate finishes.

## File Scope
Primary files:
- `src/background/utils.ts`
- `src/notification-detail/index.ts`

## Problem
Trusted image URL helpers check hostnames but not protocol. One notification-detail path fetches an SMS image before checking trust at all.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/background/utils.ts
function isTrustedImageUrl(urlString: string): boolean {
  const url = new URL(urlString);
  return (
    url.hostname.endsWith(".pushbullet.com") ||
    url.hostname.endsWith(".pushbulletusercontent.com") ||
    /^lh[0-9]\.googleusercontent\.com$/.test(url.hostname)
  );
}
```

```ts
// src/notification-detail/index.ts
if (push.type === "sms_changed" && push.notifications?.[0]?.image_url) {
  const imageUrl = push.notifications[0].image_url;
  fetch(imageUrl).then((res) => res.blob());
}
```

## Mitigation
Require HTTPS and validate before fetch/src assignment.

```ts
export function isTrustedImageUrl(urlString: string): boolean {
  try {
    const url = new URL(urlString);
    if (url.protocol !== 'https:') return false;

    return (
      url.hostname === 'pushbullet.com' ||
      url.hostname.endsWith('.pushbullet.com') ||
      url.hostname.endsWith('.pushbulletusercontent.com') ||
      /^lh[0-9]\.googleusercontent\.com$/.test(url.hostname)
    );
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- `http://sub.pushbulletusercontent.com/x.png` is rejected.
- `javascript:...`, `data:...`, and invalid URLs are rejected.
- Trusted `https://*.pushbulletusercontent.com/...` URLs still work.
- SMS contact photo fetch validates before `fetch()`.

## File Scope
Primary file: `src/app/ws/client.ts`

Consumer files:
- `src/background/index.ts`
- `src/background/state-machine.ts`

## Problem
WebSocket errors only log. Permanent closes notify the user but do not send the state machine through `WS_PERMANENT_ERROR`.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/app/ws/client.ts
this.socket.onerror = (error) => {
  debugLogger.websocket("ERROR", "WebSocket error occurred", errorInfo);
  globalErrorTracker.trackError(websocketError, {...}, "WEBSOCKET");
};
```

```ts
// src/app/ws/client.ts
this.socket.onclose = (event) => {
  globalEventBus.emit("websocket:disconnected", closeInfo);

  if (event.code === 1008 || event.code === 4001 || (event.code >= 4000 && event.code < 5000)) {
    showPermanentWebSocketError(closeInfo);
    return;
  }
};
```

## Mitigation
Classify before emitting the lifecycle event.

```ts
const permanent =
  event.code === 1008 ||
  event.code === 4001 ||
  (event.code >= 4000 && event.code < 5000);

if (permanent) {
  globalEventBus.emit('websocket:permanent-error', closeInfo);
  globalEventBus.emit('websocket:state', 'permanent-error');
  showPermanentWebSocketError(closeInfo);
  return;
}

globalEventBus.emit('websocket:disconnected', closeInfo);
```

Then wire background:

```ts
globalEventBus.on('websocket:permanent-error', async () => {
  await stateMachineReady;
  await stateMachine.transition('WS_PERMANENT_ERROR');
});
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Close code `1008` transitions to `ERROR`.
- Close code `4001` and other `4xxx` app codes transition to `ERROR`.
- Non-permanent close transitions through degraded/reconnect behavior.
- Tests assert event ordering.

## File Scope
Primary file: `src/background/index.ts`

Related files:
- `src/popup/index.ts`
- `src/app/session/index.ts`

## Problem
Opening the popup forces devices and chats network refresh before responding. On service-worker wake this adds latency and concentrates network work on the user-facing path.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/background/index.ts
if (apiKey) {
  debugLogger.general("INFO", "Force refreshing popup targets");
  const [devices, chats] = await Promise.all([
    fetchDevices(apiKey),
    fetchChats(apiKey).catch((chatError) => {
      debugLogger.general("WARN", "Failed to refresh chats for popup", {
        error: (chatError as Error).message,
      });
      return sessionCache.chats;
    }),
  ]);
  sessionCache.devices = devices;
  sessionCache.chats = chats;
}
```

## Mitigation
Respond from cache, then refresh in background.

```ts
sendResponse(buildSessionDataResponse(sessionCache));

void refreshSessionInBackground(apiKey).then(() => {
  chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
    action: MessageAction.SESSION_DATA_UPDATED,
    sessionData: buildSessionDataResponse(sessionCache),
  });
});

return true;
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Popup open responds without waiting for device/chat fetch when cache exists.
- Background refresh sends `SESSION_DATA_UPDATED` after new data arrives.
- Refresh failure keeps cached data.
- Tests cover cache hit, cache miss, and chat refresh failure.

## File Scope
Primary files:
- `src/popup/index.ts`
- `src/background/index.ts`
- `src/app/api/client.ts`

## Problem
The popup directly reads the API key and calls Pushbullet upload APIs, contradicting the background-owned API architecture.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/popup/index.ts
const uploadApiKey = await storageRepository.getApiKey();

const uploadRequestResponse = await fetch(
  "https://api.pushbullet.com/v2/upload-request",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: {
      "Access-Token": uploadApiKey,
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
    },
    body: JSON.stringify({ file_name: file.name, file_type: file.type || "application/octet-stream" }),
  },
);
```

## Mitigation
Move upload-request and final push creation into background if feasible:

```ts
// popup
chrome.runtime.sendMessage({
  action: MessageAction.UPLOAD_AND_SEND_FILE,
  file: await file.arrayBuffer(),
  fileName: file.name,
  fileType: file.type,
  target,
});
```

```ts
// background
const upload = await requestUpload(apiKey, fileName, fileType);
await uploadToS3(upload, fileBytes);
await sendFilePush(apiKey, upload.file_url, target);
```

If MV3 constraints force popup upload, document the exception in an ADR and keep token exposure narrow.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Popup no longer reads API key for upload API use, or an ADR documents why.
- Background validates file metadata before upload-request.
- Upload errors return structured responses.
- Tests cover success and upload-request failure.

## File Scope
Primary file: `src/lib/logging/index.ts`

## Problem
`debugLogger.rehydrate()` runs asynchronously at module load and replaces `this.logs` when storage returns. Logs created before rehydrate completes can be lost. `GlobalErrorTracker` also keeps unbounded arrays.

## Evidence
```ts
async rehydrate(): Promise<void> {
  const result = await chrome.storage.local.get(STORAGE_KEY);
  if (result[STORAGE_KEY] && Array.isArray(result[STORAGE_KEY])) {
    this.logs = result[STORAGE_KEY];
  }
}

debugLogger.rehydrate();
```

```ts
this.errors.push(entry);
if (count >= 5) this.criticalErrors.push(entry);
```

## Mitigation
Make initialization single-flight and merge stored with in-memory logs.

```ts
private initPromise: Promise<void> | null = null;

async ready(): Promise<void> {
  if (!this.initPromise) this.initPromise = this.rehydrateAndMerge();
  await this.initPromise;
}
```

Cap buffers:

```ts
const MAX_ERRORS = 500;
this.errors.push(entry);
if (this.errors.length > MAX_ERRORS) this.errors.shift();
this.criticalErrors = this.criticalErrors.slice(-MAX_ERRORS);
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Logs written before rehydrate finishes remain present.
- Error arrays cannot grow without bound.
- `exportErrorData()` still returns recent errors.

## File Scope
Primary file: `src/app/api/client.ts`

## Problem
Incremental fetch breaks after 10 pages even when the API returns another cursor. The caller gets a normal `Push[]` and no indication the result is incomplete.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/app/api/client.ts
page += 1;
// guard: avoid huge loops on first sync
if (page > 10) break;
```

## Mitigation
Return metadata or emit a clear warning.

```ts
interface IncrementalPushResult {
  pushes: Push[];
  truncated: boolean;
  nextCursor?: string;
  pagesFetched: number;
}
```

Minimum fix:

```ts
if (page > MAX_PAGES && cursor) {
  debugLogger.api('WARN', 'Incremental push fetch truncated', {
    pagesFetched: page,
    totalSoFar: all.length,
    hasRemainingCursor: true,
    modifiedAfter,
  });
  break;
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- Tests cover 11+ pages.
- Truncation creates a WARN log or caller-visible metadata.
- Catch-up flows have a documented stop/resume policy.

## File Scope
Primary files:
- `src/infrastructure/storage/storage.repository.ts`
- `src/options/index.ts`
- `src/background/index.ts`

## Problem
The E2EE password is stored as a plaintext string in `chrome.storage.local`. Local storage is better than sync storage, but it is still persistent extension storage.

## Evidence
```ts
// src/infrastructure/storage/storage.repository.ts
async getEncryptionPassword(): Promise<string | null> {
  const result = await chrome.storage.local.get(['encryptionPassword']);
  return getStringOrNull(result.encryptionPassword);
}

async setEncryptionPassword(password: string | null): Promise<void> {
  if (password === null) {
    await chrome.storage.local.remove(['encryptionPassword']);
  } else {
    await chrome.storage.local.set({ encryptionPassword: password });
  }
}
```

## Mitigation
Offer session-only storage by default where Chrome supports it:

```ts
await chrome.storage.session.set({ encryptionPassword: password });
```

If persistent storage remains, make it explicit:

```ts
interface EncryptionPasswordMode {
  mode: 'session' | 'persistent-local';
  hasPassword: boolean;
}
```

If the Pushbullet crypto protocol supports storing derived material instead of the raw password, prefer that. If it does not, do not imply local storage is encrypted.

## Acceptance Criteria
- User can clear the password and verify storage removal.
- Default mode does not persist the raw password across browser restarts unless user opts in.
- Debug export never includes `encryptionPassword` or derived secret material.
- Options UI distinguishes local storage from protected storage.
